 model in automata theory. In this paper, we present ENGRU (Enhanced Gated Recurrent Units), a novel deep learning-based approach for formal verification. ENGRU integrates concepts of model checking techniques, Colored Petri Nets (CPNs), and sequential learning to analyze systems at a high level of abstraction. CPN models undergo state-space enumeration via a model-checking tool, generating a state-space graph and an automaton from inherent state transition patterns. These graphs are transformed into sequential representations as sub-paths, enabling ENGRU to learn the execution paths and predict system behaviors. ENGRU effectively predicts goal states within discrete-time models by the competency of gated recurrent mechanisms, encouraging early bug detection and allowing predictive state-space exploration. Experimental results demonstrate that ENGRU’s ability achieves high accuracy and efficiency in goal state predictions.\",\"citedby-count\":\"1\",\"affiliation\": [{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"affiliation-url\":\"https://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60028190\",\"afid\":\"60028190\",\"affilname\":\"Chulalongkorn University\",\"affiliation-city\":\"Bangkok\",\"affiliation-country\":\"Thailand\"},{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"affiliation-url\":\"https://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60017165\",\"afid\":\"60017165\",\"affilname\":\"Khon Kaen University\",\"affiliation-city\":\"Khon Kaen\",\"affiliation-country\":\"Thailand\"}],\"prism:aggregationType\":\"Journal\",\"subtype\":\"ar\",\"subtypeDescription\":\"Article\",\"author-count\":{\"@limit\": \"100\", \"$\" :\"5\"},\"author\": [{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"@seq\": \"1\", \"author-url\":\"https://api.elsevier.com/content/author/author_id/54683571200\",\"authid\":\"54683571200\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0001-8441-8962\",\"authname\":\"Dechsupa C.\",\"surname\":\"Dechsupa\",\"given-name\":\"Chanon\",\"initials\":\"C.\",\"afid\": [{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"$\" :\"60017165\"}]},{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"@seq\": \"2\", \"author-url\":\"https://api.elsevier.com/content/author/author_id/57194783124\",\"authid\":\"57194783124\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0001-8464-4476\",\"authname\":\"Panboonyuen T.\",\"surname\":\"Panboonyuen\",\"given-name\":\"Teerapong\",\"initials\":\"T.\",\"afid\": [{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"$\" :\"60028190\"}]},{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"@seq\": \"3\", \"author-url\":\"https://api.elsevier.com/content/author/author_id/6507688023\",\"authid\":\"6507688023\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0003-0457-3474\",\"authname\":\"Vatanawood W.\",\"surname\":\"Vatanawood\",\"given-name\":\"Wiwat\",\"initials\":\"W.\",\"afid\": [{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"$\" :\"60028190\"}]},{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"@seq\": \"4\", \"author-url\":\"https://api.elsevier.com/content/author/author_id/35179942700\",\"authid\":\"35179942700\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0002-4358-7927\",\"authname\":\"Padungweang P.\",\"surname\":\"Padungweang\",\"given-name\":\"Praisan\",\"initials\":\"P.\",\"afid\": [{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"$\" :\"60017165\"}]},{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"@seq\": \"5\", \"author-url\":\"https://api.elsevier.com/content/author/author_id/57218454758\",\"authid\":\"57218454758\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0003-1026-191X\",\"authname\":\"So-In C.\",\"surname\":\"So-In\",\"given-name\":\"Chakchai\",\"initials\":\"C.\",\"afid\": [{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"$\" :\"60017165\"}]}],\"authkeywords\":\"colored petri net | formal verification | GRU attention | Model checking | state-space analysis\",\"source-id\":\"21100374601\",\"fund-acr\":\"KKU\",\"fund-sponsor\":\"Khon Kaen University\",\"openaccess\":\"1\",\"openaccessFlag\":true,\"freetoread\":{\"value\": [{\"$\" :\"all\"},{\"$\" :\"publisherfullgold\"}]},\"freetoreadLabel\":{\"value\": [{\"$\" :\"All Open Access\"},{\"$\" :\"Gold\"}]}}', '2025-11-12 02:28:49', '2025-12-06 14:53:55'),
(4, '2-s2.0-85216590998', 'SCOPUS_ID:85216590998', 'https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&scp=85216590998&origin=inward', 'Ensuring IoT Controller Reliability with Colored Generalized Stochastic Petri Net', 'In IoT systems managing multiple devices simultaneously, errors in system controllers often undermine intended operations. Formal verification offers a method to assess system reliability. Colored Generalized Stochastic Petri Net (CGSPN), a formal language, facilitate correctness checks of such systems. This study proposes a verification approach by translating a C++-based system controller of a self-service machine into a CGSPN models and validating it using the Snoopy Tool. Mapping techniques employed to transform components in the controller into CGSPN models are provided. Results demonstrate the method\'s efficacy in verifying system safety properties, simulating system events, and enabling quantitative verification.', 'Journal', 'cp', 'Conference Paper', '21101272039', 'International Computer Science and Engineering Conference', '23815035', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024', NULL, NULL, '2024-01-01', '2024', '10.1109/ICSEC62781.2024.10770732', NULL, 0, 0, 0, '[\"Colored Stochastic Petri net\",\"Formal model\",\"Internet of things\",\"Safety properties\"]', 'KKU', 'Khon Kaen University', '{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"link\": [{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"@ref\": \"self\", \"@href\": \"https://api.elsevier.com/content/abstract/scopus_id/85216590998\"},{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"@ref\": \"author-affiliation\", \"@href\": \"https://api.elsevier.com/content/abstract/scopus_id/85216590998?field=author,affiliation\"},{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"@ref\": \"scopus\", \"@href\": \"https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&scp=85216590998&origin=inward\"},{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"@ref\": \"scopus-citedby\", \"@href\": \"https://www.scopus.com/inward/citedby.uri?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&scp=85216590998&origin=inward\"}],\"prism:url\":\"https://api.elsevier.com/content/abstract/scopus_id/85216590998\",\"dc:identifier\":\"SCOPUS_ID:85216590998\",\"eid\":\"2-s2.0-85216590998\",\"dc:title\":\"Ensuring IoT Controller Reliability with Colored Generalized Stochastic Petri Net\",\"dc:creator\":\"Samngamnoi K.\",\"prism:publicationName\":\"International Computer Science and Engineering Conference\",\"prism:issn\":\"23815035\",\"prism:issueIdentifier\":\"2024\",\"prism:pageRange\":null,\"prism:coverDate\":\"2024-01-01\",\"prism:coverDisplayDate\":\"2024\",\"prism:doi\":\"10.1109/ICSEC62781.2024.10770732\",\"dc:description\":\"In IoT systems managing multiple devices simultaneously, errors in system controllers often undermine intended operations. Formal verification offers a method to assess system reliability. Colored Generalized Stochastic Petri Net (CGSPN), a formal language, facilitate correctness checks of such systems. This study proposes a verification approach by translating a C++-based system controller of a self-service machine into a CGSPN models and validating it using the Snoopy Tool. Mapping techniques employed to transform components in the controller into CGSPN models are provided. Results demonstrate the method\'s efficacy in verifying system safety properties, simulating system events, and enabling quantitative verification.\",\"citedby-count\":\"0\",\"affiliation\": [{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"affiliation-url\":\"https://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60017165\",\"afid\":\"60017165\",\"affilname\":\"Khon Kaen University\",\"affiliation-city\":\"Khon Kaen\",\"affiliation-country\":\"Thailand\"}],\"prism:aggregationType\":\"Journal\",\"subtype\":\"cp\",\"subtypeDescription\":\"Conference Paper\",\"author-count\":{\"@limit\": \"100\", \"$\" :\"4\"},\"author\": [{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"@seq\": \"1\", \"author-url\":\"https://api.elsevier.com/content/author/author_id/59536116000\",\"authid\":\"59536116000\",\"authname\":\"Samngamnoi K.\",\"surname\":\"Samngamnoi\",\"given-name\":\"Kruntarat\",\"initials\":\"K.\",\"afid\": [{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"$\" :\"60017165\"}]},{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"@seq\": \"2\", \"author-url\":\"https://api.elsevier.com/content/author/author_id/59320982800\",\"authid\":\"59320982800\",\"authname\":\"Pomsiri S.\",\"surname\":\"Pomsiri\",\"given-name\":\"Sutinun\",\"initials\":\"S.\",\"afid\": [{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"$\" :\"60017165\"}]},{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"@seq\": \"3\", \"author-url\":\"https://api.elsevier.com/content/author/author_id/58571756600\",\"authid\":\"58571756600\",\"authname\":\"Kamput A.\",\"surname\":\"Kamput\",\"given-name\":\"Apipath\",\"initials\":\"A.\",\"afid\": [{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"$\" :\"60017165\"}]},{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"@seq\": \"4\", \"author-url\":\"https://api.elsevier.com/content/author/author_id/54683571200\",\"authid\":\"54683571200\",\"authname\":\"Dechsupa C.\",\"surname\":\"Dechsupa\",\"given-name\":\"Chanon\",\"initials\":\"C.\",\"afid\": [{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"$\" :\"60017165\"}]}],\"authkeywords\":\"Colored Stochastic Petri net | Formal model | Internet of things | Safety properties\",\"source-id\":\"21101272039\",\"fund-acr\":\"KKU\",\"fund-sponsor\":\"Khon Kaen University\",\"openaccess\":\"0\",\"openaccessFlag\":false}', '2025-11-12 02:28:49', '2025-12-06 14:53:55'),
(5, '2-s2.0-85203541294', 'SCOPUS_ID:85203541294', 'https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&scp=85203541294&origin=inward', 'Scalable Timed-Automata Models for Traffic Light Control Systems: Challenges and Solutions in Formal Verification', 'Modeling and verification are crucial in designing traffic light control systems, guaranteeing these systems meet desired operational properties and handle dynamic traffic conditions effectively. The design process involves addressing complexities such as route intricacy, congestion, timing, and prioritization, especially important in areas with multiple interconnected intersections. A key aspect of this process is developing a scalable model, essential for adapting to various traffic scenarios and intersection configurations. This paper presents a method using UPPAAL, a timed-automata tool, for modeling and verifying smart traffic light systems. We focus on creating scalable models, facilitating effective synchronization across intersections. Our approach includes templates and frameworks to assist in formalizing traffic light designs, emphasizing verification of safety, structural integrity, and performance. The results of our study reveal a significant usability in verification approaches through the use of formal model templates. Additionally, the model\'s phases and stages, complete with adaptable time schedules, show flexibility in environments with variable parameters.', 'Journal', 'ar', 'Article', '21100374601', 'IEEE Access', NULL, '21693536', NULL, '12', NULL, '124260-124281', NULL, '2024-01-01', '2024', '10.1109/ACCESS.2024.3455097', NULL, 3, 1, 1, '[\"Formal verification\",\"model checking\",\"safety property\",\"timed automata\",\"traffic control systems\",\"UPPAAL\"]', 'KKU', 'Khon Kaen University', '{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"link\": [{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"@ref\": \"self\", \"@href\": \"https://api.elsevier.com/content/abstract/scopus_id/85203541294\"},{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"@ref\": \"author-affil