(7, '2-s2.0-85170521704', 'SCOPUS_ID:85170521704', 'https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&scp=85170521704&origin=inward', 'Formal Modelling and Verification of the Traffic Light Control System Design with Time-Automata', 'Modelling and verification are important procedures in traffic light design because they check the model’s correctness and determine whether it has desirable properties or not. The traffic light design models must be verified before implementation. Especially in synchronized traffic light intersection systems, where the traffic lights at the multiple intersections require many communication channels for synchronization of the message among intersections and traffic light groups, the traffic light model must be proven meticulously. This paper proposed the modelling and verification of the traffic-right design models by using a time automata named Uppaal. Our templates and frameworks help the modellers create the traffic-right designs in a formal model and can verify the safety properties and structure of the model correctly.', 'Conference Proceeding', 'cp', 'Conference Paper', '21100218002', 'Lecture Notes in Engineering and Computer Science', '20780958', '20780966', '[9789881404947]', '2245', NULL, '36-41', NULL, '2023-01-01', '2023', NULL, NULL, 2, 0, 0, '[\"Formal modelling\",\"Model checking\",\"Software engineering\",\"Time automata\",\"Traffic right design\"]', NULL, NULL, '{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"link\": [{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"@ref\": \"self\", \"@href\": \"https://api.elsevier.com/content/abstract/scopus_id/85170521704\"},{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"@ref\": \"author-affiliation\", \"@href\": \"https://api.elsevier.com/content/abstract/scopus_id/85170521704?field=author,affiliation\"},{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"@ref\": \"scopus\", \"@href\": \"https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&scp=85170521704&origin=inward\"},{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"@ref\": \"scopus-citedby\", \"@href\": \"https://www.scopus.com/inward/citedby.uri?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&scp=85170521704&origin=inward\"}],\"prism:url\":\"https://api.elsevier.com/content/abstract/scopus_id/85170521704\",\"dc:identifier\":\"SCOPUS_ID:85170521704\",\"eid\":\"2-s2.0-85170521704\",\"dc:title\":\"Formal Modelling and Verification of the Traffic Light Control System Design with Time-Automata\",\"dc:creator\":\"Kamput A.\",\"prism:publicationName\":\"Lecture Notes in Engineering and Computer Science\",\"prism:issn\":\"20780958\",\"prism:eIssn\":\"20780966\",\"prism:isbn\": [{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"$\" :\"[9789881404947]\"}],\"prism:volume\":\"2245\",\"prism:pageRange\":\"36-41\",\"prism:coverDate\":\"2023-01-01\",\"prism:coverDisplayDate\":\"2023\",\"dc:description\":\"Modelling and verification are important procedures in traffic light design because they check the model’s correctness and determine whether it has desirable properties or not. The traffic light design models must be verified before implementation. Especially in synchronized traffic light intersection systems, where the traffic lights at the multiple intersections require many communication channels for synchronization of the message among intersections and traffic light groups, the traffic light model must be proven meticulously. This paper proposed the modelling and verification of the traffic-right design models by using a time automata named Uppaal. Our templates and frameworks help the modellers create the traffic-right designs in a formal model and can verify the safety properties and structure of the model correctly.\",\"citedby-count\":\"2\",\"affiliation\": [{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"affiliation-url\":\"https://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60017165\",\"afid\":\"60017165\",\"affilname\":\"Khon Kaen University\",\"affiliation-city\":\"Khon Kaen\",\"affiliation-country\":\"Thailand\"}],\"prism:aggregationType\":\"Conference Proceeding\",\"subtype\":\"cp\",\"subtypeDescription\":\"Conference Paper\",\"author-count\":{\"@limit\": \"100\", \"$\" :\"2\"},\"author\": [{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"@seq\": \"1\", \"author-url\":\"https://api.elsevier.com/content/author/author_id/58571756600\",\"authid\":\"58571756600\",\"authname\":\"Kamput A.\",\"surname\":\"Kamput\",\"given-name\":\"A.\",\"initials\":\"A.\",\"afid\": [{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"$\" :\"60017165\"}]},{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"@seq\": \"2\", \"author-url\":\"https://api.elsevier.com/content/author/author_id/54683571200\",\"authid\":\"54683571200\",\"authname\":\"Dechsupa C.\",\"surname\":\"Dechsupa\",\"given-name\":\"C.\",\"initials\":\"C.\",\"afid\": [{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"$\" :\"60017165\"}]}],\"authkeywords\":\"Formal modelling | Model checking | Software engineering | Time automata | Traffic right design\",\"source-id\":\"21100218002\",\"openaccess\":\"0\",\"openaccessFlag\":false}', '2025-11-12 02:28:49', '2025-12-06 14:53:56'),
(8, '2-s2.0-85170557468', 'SCOPUS_ID:85170557468', 'https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&scp=85170557468&origin=inward', 'Transforming of the Sequence Diagram into Time-Automata Network', 'Formal verification using a model checking approach is a process for proving undesirable properties in designed models. The model checking procedure for the sequence diagram is cumbersome because the transformation of the sequence diagram into a formal model requires meticulous mapping rules and methods that must yield corresponding behaviors. This paper proposes the transformation of the sequence diagram into a time automate named UPPAAL. The obtained time automata model can be used to verify deadlock, undesirable properties, and the correctness of message ordering. The transformation rules and framework were experimented with case studies. The results show that the proposed transformation rules can be applied and map the sequence diagram into a UPPAL structure correctly.', 'Conference Proceeding', 'cp', 'Conference Paper', '21100218002', 'Lecture Notes in Engineering and Computer Science', '20780958', '20780966', '[9789881404947]', '2245', NULL, '147-152', NULL, '2023-01-01', '2023', NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 0, '[\"Formal verification\",\"Software engineering\",\"Time automata\",\"UML sequence diagram\"]', NULL, NULL, '{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"link\": [{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"@ref\": \"self\", \"@href\": \"https://api.elsevier.com/content/abstract/scopus_id/85170557468\"},{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"@ref\": \"author-affiliation\", \"@href\": \"https://api.elsevier.com/content/abstract/scopus_id/85170557468?field=author,affiliation\"},{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"@ref\": \"scopus\", \"@href\": \"https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&scp=85170557468&origin=inward\"},{\"@_fa\": \"true\", \"@ref\": \"scopus-citedby\", \"@href\": \"https://www.scopus.com/inward/citedby.uri?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&scp=85170557468&origin=inward\"}],\"prism:url\":\"https://api.elsevie